  "summary": "Yuki and Yuzu engage in a philosophical discussion regarding darkness and light. Yuki suggests that even pitch-black darkness eventually fades to purple, noting that even the Snow Queen Selene found peace in a world without light. Yuzu remarks on the melancholy of the night and the inability of flowers to bloom in the lightless city of Xiangyuan. Yuzu suggests that the \"white raven\" is no longer a raven and warns the narrator not to think too much about the matter before walking away.\n\nThe narrator, Kouki, later finds Mizuho sitting in the courtyard of the Inari household, which resembles a small botanical garden. Mizuho, wearing a white dress, appears pale and describes a sense of something \"terrifying\" within the city. She suffers a coughing fit, attributing her poor health to the changing seasons. Mizuho expresses deep trust in Mr. Kimitsuki, whom she compares to a god, and believes he will rid the household of its terrors. Kouki attempts to encourage her, suggesting that trust brings redemption.\n\nAs Kouki leaves, he encounters Mukae, who mocks his gentlemanly behavior. Kouki expresses concern that Mizuho seems to be on the brink of death. Mukae and Muto discuss the underlying reasons for her condition, revealing that Mizuho is the daughter of a mistress. Muto explains that the Kaga family only recently acknowledged Kaguya, following a relationship twenty years ago involving Kanou and a woman he nearly ran away with.",
